Search across Jira, Slack, Gmail, and any shared documents or meeting notes from the past 2 weeks. First, determine whether I manage a team by checking for direct reports in Workday or the people directory. If unclear, ask me: "Do you manage direct reports, or are you looking for visibility into your peers and collaborators?"

IF I'M A MANAGER — give me a team pulse check.

For each member of my direct team:

NAME & ROLE

ACTIVE WORK — what are they actually spending time on right now? Be specific with project names and ticket IDs where available. Tag with SOURCE ATTRIBUTION.

GREEN FLAGS — anything they're executing well, moving fast on, or contributing meaningfully to. Call it out specifically, don't just say "doing well."

WATCH ITEMS — anything stalled, deprioritized, going quiet, or where output seems below their normal pace. Don't sugarcoat this.

INITIATIVE ALIGNMENT — does their current work ladder up to the team's major initiatives, or does it look disconnected or reactive?

After covering the full team:

TEAM STATE OF PLAY — one paragraph with your honest read: where is the team firing, where is there drag, and is there anything I should address as a manager this week? Name names. No feel-good summary.

MISALIGNMENT CHECK — what percentage of the team's collective effort connects to our top 3 initiatives? If significant work is happening outside those priorities, flag it and name it.

RECOGNITION & SUPPORT — Based on what you see, recommend:
• Who deserves recognition this week, and for what specifically? Not generic praise, name the specific contribution and suggest the right channel (public Slack shoutout, 1:1 acknowledgment, mention to their skip-level).
• Who looks like they could use help, air cover, or a check-in? What signals suggest this (going quiet, overloaded, blocked, working on something alone that should be collaborative)?
• For each, offer to draft the message: a recognition note, a "how can I help" check-in, or a "let me clear the path" escalation.

For any watch items, offer to draft a Slack or email to the relevant person to check in.

IF I'M AN INDIVIDUAL CONTRIBUTOR — give me a peer landscape scan.

Identify my closest collaborators and cross-functional partners based on communication patterns (who I email, Slack, and meet with most). For each:

NAME & ROLE

WHAT THEY'RE FOCUSED ON — based on their visible activity in Slack, Jira, and shared documents. What are their current priorities?

WHERE WE INTERSECT — shared projects, tickets, meetings, or threads. What are we actively working on together?

OPEN COMMITMENTS — what do I owe them, and what do they owe me? Use COMMITMENT LEDGER format.

THEIR PACE — are they responsive and engaged, or have they gone quiet recently? Flag any changes.

After covering key collaborators:

LANDSCAPE READ — one paragraph on what my immediate professional environment looks like right now. Who's moving fast, who's heads down, who might need something from me that I haven't noticed?

COLLABORATION OPPORTUNITY — is there someone in my orbit working on something adjacent to my priorities that I should connect with? Be specific about why and what the opening would be.

WHERE I CAN ADD VALUE — Based on what my peers are working on, is there someone I could proactively offer help to? Look for: someone stuck on something I have experience with, someone working on a problem I've already solved, or someone whose workstream would benefit from what I'm building. Suggest the specific offer and the channel. Offer to draft the message.

Keep both modes under 500 words. Be specific, name names, use ticket IDs where available.
